 <span style="color:rgb(191, 134, 96);font-style:italic;">Mon, 10 Oct 2005 14:33:05, Uncle Bob., Code that's not unit testable. </span>
	<div style="margin:0px 0px 0px 15px;display:block;">I have another rule.  It's not part of the three, but it is part of my personal repertoire.  <i>Rule 4: There is no such thing as untestable code.</i>.  Is this rule true?  I don't know for sure.  However, I treat it as an attitude.  I refuse to believe that, given appropriate creativity and imagination, there is some code that cannot be tested.  Indeed, I refuse to believe that, given appropriate creativity and imagination, there is code that cannot be <i>profitably</i> tested.<br clear="none"/><br clear="none"/>Accepting that there are certain kinds of code that are &quot;impossible&quot; to test is a slippery slope.  It's an excuse to abandon creativity, and submit to the siren song of the schedule that whispers that you don't have time, you don't have time, you don't have time.<br clear="none"/><br clear="none"/>If you have code that you believe cannot be tested, then I suggest that you:<br clear="none"/><ol style="padding-left:1.3em;margin:0px;list-style-position:inside;text-indent:-1.3em;"><li style="margin:5px;">Stop, and find a way to test it.</li><li style="margin:5px;">Find a way to change it so that it's testable.</li></ol>
</div>
</div>
<div style="background-color:rgb(249, 249, 249);margin:5px 0px;padding:2px;border:1px dotted rgb(144, 144, 144);border-color:rgb(191, 134, 96);">
