 <span style="color:rgb(191, 134, 96);font-style:italic;">Tue, 11 Oct 2005 09:44:13, Sebastian Kuebeck, </span>
	<div style="margin:0px 0px 0px 15px;display:block;">Great point! I'd make Rule 4 actually Rule 1 since it's the most important!<br clear="none"/>I absolutely agree with your opinion that everything should be tested automatically.<br clear="none"/>The point is the time a test takes to run.<br clear="none"/>I keep slow tests (e.g. calls to stored procedures that need to shouvle around some data<br clear="none"/>between a number of tables) in a different directory than the quick ones that drive my<br clear="none"/>development so I'm not blocked by slow infrastructure during development<br clear="none"/>(TDD is a different word for green arrow obsession ;-) ).<br clear="none"/>I call the slow ones also frequently, especially before or during I take a break.<br clear="none"/>Maybe I'm wrong but I thought only the quick ones where called unit tests and the<br clear="none"/>slow ones integration or whatever tests, that's all.</div>
</div>
<div style="background-color:rgb(249, 249, 249);margin:5px 0px;padding:2px;border:1px dotted rgb(144, 144, 144);border-color:rgb(191, 134, 96);">
