 <span style="color:rgb(191, 134, 96);font-style:italic;">Sat, 3 Dec 2005 19:21:37, Uncle Bob, Bah: We never deliver anything. </span>
	<div style="margin:0px 0px 0px 15px;display:block;"><table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="font-size:inherit;font-weight:inherit;font-style:inherit;font-variant:inherit;border:solid rgb(119, 119, 119);background-color:rgb(248, 248, 248);margin:0px;padding:0px;border-width:1px 0px 0px 1px;"><tr><td colspan="1" rowspan="1" style="border:solid rgb(119, 119, 119);border-width:0px 1px 1px 0px;padding:5px;">John Cowan said:<i>Type the first character of a test, compile it; it fails, naturally. Type the next character of a test, compile it; it fails, naturally. Repeat. We keep rules 1, 2, and 3, but we never deliver anything.</i></td></tr></table>
<br clear="none"/>John,  Perhaps you are taking this too literally.  There are many examples available for how to apply these laws.  Consider, for example, <a shape="rect" href="http://butunclebob.com/ArticleS.UncleBob.TheBowlingGameKata" style="background-color:transparent;color:rgb(97, 128, 89);">TheBowlingGameKata</a>.</div>
</div>
<div style="background-color:rgb(249, 249, 249);margin:5px 0px;padding:2px;border:1px dotted rgb(144, 144, 144);border-color:rgb(191, 134, 96);">
	<div style="color:rgb(191, 134, 96);font-style:italic;float:right;"><a shape="rect" href="#" style="background-color:transparent;color:rgb(97, 128, 89);">Expand All</a> | <a shape="rect" href="#" style="background-color:transparent;color:rgb(97, 128, 89);">Collapse All</a></div>
