	</a>
 <span style="color:rgb(191, 134, 96);font-style:italic;">Sat, 3 Dec 2005 19:28:56, Uncle Bob, 1000s of test cases. </span>
	<div style="margin:0px 0px 0px 15px;display:block;">Yes, there can be thousands of test cases.  The more production code you have, the more test cases you will have.  Fortunately, the structure of the tests mimics the structure of the production code.  For every class, there is often a corresponding test-class.  This test-class describes how the class works, how to call it, and what to expect from it.  Personally, I keep the test classes in the same package as the production code class.  So when I look in my IDE I see the class, and the test-class right next to each other.  That's <i>very</i> nice.</div>
</div>
<div style="background-color:rgb(249, 249, 249);margin:5px 0px;padding:2px;border:1px dotted rgb(144, 144, 144);border-color:rgb(191, 134, 96);">
